<subSubSection id="A5092E42D7369C65C8B6ED74FF939B18" pageId="0" pageNumber="61" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="FC7BE2BA1CC8BEAC22F747A8C687E3D9" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FA011F120A8051142F5E1CD2A549400A" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">
<taxonomicName id="461F1782E8734DA4018A2160A8FD2D18" authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1852" class="Insecta" family="Coccinellidae" genus="Coccidula" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Coccidula lepida" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="61" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lepida">
<emphasis id="FC48CBBAB44F6BC031C2A461AA685C63" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">Coccidula lepida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only Nearctic species of the genus, and is similar in many characters to 
<taxonomicName id="398491D1E027BFB55D9EBD70EDE95E11" family="Coccinellidae" genus="C." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="C. scutellata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="61" rank="species" species="scutellata">
<emphasis id="9510C781761E9CCE4D35BC09F00AA90F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">C. scutellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but with the head and epipleura black. In the typical form (
<taxonomicName id="7F2BB48AD5CE95F39C584EFE161BB54D" family="Coccinellidae" genus="C." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="C. lepida" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="61" rank="species" species="lepida">
<emphasis id="CF9E0F2FBB6A5C72380879AA6B02925D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">C. lepida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described by LeConte), the black elytral pattern resembles an extension of the five fused black maculae on the elytra of 
<taxonomicName id="6BB6430CD24BD3D316273F5BEA4406FE" family="Coccinellidae" genus="C." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="C. scutellata" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="61" rank="species" species="scutellata">
<emphasis id="05B5E400B998EBCA41E1409B3C18E1C3" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">C. scutellata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with shoulders and epipleura black. Shoulder tubercle distinct, prototum relatively narrow. Male genitalia with penis guide much shorter than parameres. Detailed description of morphology including variability in pattern can be found in 
<bibRefCitation id="3BC0F77199CCBB719F816C9CE72DDBFF" author="Gordon, RD" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the New York Entomological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="61" pagination="1 - 912" refId="B17" refString="Gordon, RD, 1985. The Coccinellidae (Coleoptera) of America north of Mexico. Journal of the New York Entomological Society 93 (1): 1 - 912" title="The Coccinellidae (Coleoptera) of America north of Mexico." volume="93" year="1985">Gordon (1985</bibRefCitation>
: 656-659).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8031D65BE27CF10C0E5EBD051DB56107" pageId="0" pageNumber="61" type="description">
<paragraph id="0A422513FB4A69FD4A4184E683370D79" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0A3415844105E5FEAB413AF85DD57DE6" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">Length = 2.7-3.5 mm, BL/BW = 1.88-1.96, EL/BW = 1.40-1.42, PW/BW = 0.73.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F350D89EE43BC96EA361FACFE1AE539F" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">
Body elongate (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4ADBDBB6DACE4AC29E1CC9E4790D24C5" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Immature stages and habitus of adult species of Coccidula Kugelann A C. rufa larva B C. rufa pupa C C. lepida, dorsal D C. lepida, ventral E C. litophiloides F C. reitteri G C. rufa H C. scutellata A, B Gilles San Martin, Wikimedia Commons C, D Danny Haelewaters G, H Udo Schmidt. Scale bars: 1 mm (C-H)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.65829.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554376" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">1C</figureCitation>
), slightly widening in posterior part. Head black. Elytra of typical form, light testaceous with black pattern covering scutellar shield and surrounding portion of elytra through shoulders to lateral margins, covering about 60% of its anterior part; pair of maculae in posterior 3/4 of elytra near suture; in western population fused and connected to scutellar shield over suture. Ventral side (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B60E4D5B318501298F9C58DDE2652438" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Immature stages and habitus of adult species of Coccidula Kugelann A C. rufa larva B C. rufa pupa C C. lepida, dorsal D C. lepida, ventral E C. litophiloides F C. reitteri G C. rufa H C. scutellata A, B Gilles San Martin, Wikimedia Commons C, D Danny Haelewaters G, H Udo Schmidt. Scale bars: 1 mm (C-H)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.65829.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554376" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">1D</figureCitation>
) black with hypomera and ventrites 3-6 testaceous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="DAF8BA98865401C6C5BF05986812DB99" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">
Head and pronotum covered with uniform small setiferous punctures arranged irregularly. Pronotum transverse, broadly rounded laterally, with lateral margin glabrous; pronotum covered with dense setiferous punctures. Posterior pronotal corners not produced (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="66A0169BFC7A3C1BEF5737B34207C88E" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Coccidula lepida LeConte SEM illustrations A pronotum B head and prothorax, ventral C meso and metaventrite D elytra dorsal E ventrite 1. Scale bars: 500 Âµm (A-C); 1 mm (E, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.65829.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554377" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">2A</figureCitation>
). Prosternum with anterior margin with bordering line complete. Prosternal process with complete lateral carinae, joined roundly and merged with anterior border of pronotum (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D0E4E8324BC971ADB82EEE8545F0CDDD" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Coccidula lepida LeConte SEM illustrations A pronotum B head and prothorax, ventral C meso and metaventrite D elytra dorsal E ventrite 1. Scale bars: 500 Âµm (A-C); 1 mm (E, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.65829.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554377" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">2B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="44C7A9B3A4A1F7E9CAD27CC4665C3024" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">
Scutellar shield pentagonal, covered with dense setiferous punctures. Elytra (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6A4FA12702706ED38324FB5D25FA453F" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Coccidula lepida LeConte SEM illustrations A pronotum B head and prothorax, ventral C meso and metaventrite D elytra dorsal E ventrite 1. Scale bars: 500 Âµm (A-C); 1 mm (E, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.65829.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554377" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">2D</figureCitation>
) covered with two types of punctures, small setiferous punctures irregularly distributed throughout the elytral surface, some of these punctures surrounded by larger depressed circles forming nine irregular longitudinal rows along the whole length of elytra. Shoulder tubercles distinct, but lateral elytral margin of elytra visible from above throughout. Mesoventrite (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="AD1897CB2ED4BA101F34F21F1016149A" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Coccidula lepida LeConte SEM illustrations A pronotum B head and prothorax, ventral C meso and metaventrite D elytra dorsal E ventrite 1. Scale bars: 500 Âµm (A-C); 1 mm (E, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.65829.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554377" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">2C</figureCitation>
) with anterior border interrupted in median part. Metaventrite (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="012EE15427A8D548C5ED124F7BB7E602" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Coccidula lepida LeConte SEM illustrations A pronotum B head and prothorax, ventral C meso and metaventrite D elytra dorsal E ventrite 1. Scale bars: 500 Âµm (A-C); 1 mm (E, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.65829.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554377" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">2C</figureCitation>
) with postcoxal lines transverse in median part and then descending laterally, continuous on the metaventral process in median part; covered with setiferous punctures very sparsely distributed in central part of sclerite, densely setose in anterolateral parts, with a single row of large punctures below postcoxal lines and above metacoxae.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="15E8147BD2908FFB4D81A44B5B2923C4" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">
Abdominal postcoxal lines (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5CD0AFB7E8D2D83F45B476C49DD4040F" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Coccidula lepida LeConte SEM illustrations A pronotum B head and prothorax, ventral C meso and metaventrite D elytra dorsal E ventrite 1. Scale bars: 500 Âµm (A-C); 1 mm (E, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1043.65829.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/554377" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">2E</figureCitation>
) complete, widely rounded, reaching about half of the length of the ventrite 1 measured below metacoxa. Ventrites covered with dense setiferous punctures.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="48CAA641CE99FF0B6C6CB339B69824FF" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="B0147AAD98E74BF55D22F8C32D1FA5C1" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="49BE1DCADDD44998FE18834DBCD74EAF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">Male genitalia</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Tegmen in inner view with penis guide subtriangular with pointed apex; short, about two times shorter than parameres. Parameres elongate elliptical, inner surface smooth, with long setae on the inner side and in apical margin. Penis simple with pointed apex. [see 
<bibRefCitation id="D5C741870AE06F04E875F2DD6883095E" author="Gordon, RD" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the New York Entomological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="61" pagination="1 - 912" refId="B17" refString="Gordon, RD, 1985. The Coccinellidae (Coleoptera) of America north of Mexico. Journal of the New York Entomological Society 93 (1): 1 - 912" title="The Coccinellidae (Coleoptera) of America north of Mexico." volume="93" year="1985">Gordon 1985</bibRefCitation>
: 657, fig. 539 a-d]
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9CFB3110E5712DDECAB27B7415A040F5" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="9C26886F89D7F82E8EE9E3B2B702C24A" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">
<emphasis id="DC64574AB55183E4E0F9BD51CA5D5A9C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="61">Female genitalia</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Sperm duct long, much longer than length of spermatheca. Spermatheca vermiform, broadest in basal part. [see 
<bibRefCitation id="307C53A567FA6DA28A92B009F0BEC2E9" author="Gordon, RD" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the New York Entomological Society" pageId="0" pageNumber="61" pagination="1 - 912" refId="B17" refString="Gordon, RD, 1985. The Coccinellidae (Coleoptera) of America north of Mexico. Journal of the New York Entomological Society 93 (1): 1 - 912" title="The Coccinellidae (Coleoptera) of America north of Mexico." volume="93" year="1985">Gordon 1985</bibRefCitation>
: 657, fig. 539e]
</paragraph>
